The paper deals with a distributed algorithm for consensus in a networked system, which is a common topic in the Distributed Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. The use of a time-varying topology and the absence of strong connectivity properties suggest that the paper may also be relevant to the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category. The algorithmic nature of the paper and the focus on efficiency in terms of message size and storage requirements suggest that it may also be relevant to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. The use of a synchronous model and the requirement for a root agent to send messages suggest that the paper may also be relevant to the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-category. Finally, the focus on stabilizing consensus in a networked system suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category.
